scope_note: The state of Hessen occupies 8,152 square miles in north-central Germany. Its territory forms the core of the medieval margraviate of Hessen, and extends west to east from the Rhine Plateau to the Thuringian Forest. The original landmargraviate of Hesse was founded from a portion of Thuringia. Its ruler, Henry I, came to hold the rank of prince in the Holy Roman Empire in 1292. Under Philip the Magnanimous, Hesse was twice partitioned and reunited, finally to be divided into four sections, one for each of his sons. In 1945 the modern state was created from the Hesse territories and part of Nassau. The capital is Wiesbaden and its largest city is Frankfurt am Main. The state is known for its educational institutions, and for the ruined castles and old churches along the Weser River, and the many half-timbered houses scattered throughout. The economy features agriculture on small or large scales, and a great deal of manufacturing, primarily in the south. The 2004 estimated population was 6,105,200
wikidata_description: state in the center of Germany

scope_note: Bavaria is the largest state in the nation of Germany, comprising the entire southeast portion of the country. The land consists mainly of mountains and high plateaus, measuring some 27,241 square miles in area. The area was inhabited by Celts in centuries before the Common Era. It was conquered by Rome in 38 BCE, ravaged by Lombards in the 5th century, then settled by Marcomanni and Baiuoarii ca. 520. It formed the core of the Frankish dukedom from the 6th century, and became Christian by the 9th century. In 788, Charlemagne overthrew the last Frankish duke and brought Bavaria into the Carolingian Empire. It joined the Holy Roman Empire in the 10th century. In 1180 the emperor gave Bavaria to the count palatine Otto of Wittelsbach, the founder of the powerful dynasty that ruled Bavarian until 1918. Bavaria greatly expanded its territory over time, though it suffered greatly during the War of Spanish Succession. In the 18th century it first opposed then allied itself with Napoleonic France, and in 1805 was elevated from a duchy to a kingdom. The kingdom switched allegiance between Austria and Prussia several times in the turbulent 19th century, finally joining the German Empire under Prussian leadership. It retained a great deal of autonomy however, in 1918 the royal dynasty was deposed and after much civil strife, in August 1919 Bavaria joined the Weimar Republic. After World War II, Bavaria was in the American-occupied zone, and became a state in the new Federal Republic of Germany. The modern state's economy is largely industry- and trade-based, with forestry and agriculture constituting only about 10%. The state has a rich cultural life, with music and theater taking high prominent, and traditional folk art still strong. The capital is Munich. The 2004 estimated population was 10,902,600.
wikidata_description: federated state in the south of Germany

scope_note: Area was core of ancient Etruria; conquered by Romans 4th century BCE; ruled by Lombards, then Franks; most cities became independent communes 11th-12th centuries; saw great strife between Guelphs and Ghibellines; part of grand duchy of Florence from the 16th century.
Region of Italy comprising a hilly area with a narrow coastal plain in central Italy. Modern adminisrative region includes a part of the territory of ancient Latium.

wikidata_description: federated state, capital and largest city of Germany

scope_note: The state of North Rhine-Westphalia is located in west central Germany. It lies bordered by Belgium and the Netherlands to the west, Hesse to the east, Lower Saxony to the north, and Rhineland-Palatinate to the south.  It was formed after World War II of an amalgamation of Prussian Westfalen, the Northeim province of Prussia, and the state of Lippe. The area suffered extensive damage during World War II. The state has since grown and developed into Germany's industrial heartland, including the Saarland region, and contains one-fifth of its total population, 18,100,000 by a 2004 estimate.

Baden-Württemberg is a state in southwestern Germany, bordered by Switzerland in the south, France to the west, the state of Bavaria on the east, Rhineland-Palatinate on the northeast, and Hesse to the north. It measures some 13,804 square miles in area. Most of its people are Alemanni, relatives of the French Alsatians, plus Franconians, Palatinate people, and Swabians. Before the Romans occupied it, the main European trading artery was the River Rhein which runs through Baden-Württemberg. It also had immense hardwood forests, now largely cut. To the south are the Alps. The state was formed in the post-World War II occupational period from three former states in the American and French zones; this arrangement was ratified by a referendum in 1951 and made official in 1952. Its capital is Stuttgart. The 2004 estimated population was 10,721,600.
wikidata_description: state in the southwest of the Federal Republic of Germany

scope_note: Area was political center of old France, and has been hub of France ever since; most densely populated region of France; in addition to large uban area around Paris, is noted for fertile fields in outlying areas; see historical region, Île-de-France.

Settled by ancient Celtic people (Veneti) in 1st mill. BCE; ruled by Rome from 2nd cen. BCE; invaded by Huns in mid-5th cen. CE; area gained financial and military prominence in 15th cen.; was passed between France and Austria during 18th-19th cen.

Inhabited by Gallic people; part of Roman Cisalpine Gaul from 3rd century BCE; core of Germanic Lombard kingdom from 569; ruled by Charlemagne from 774, by bishops of Milan from the 11th century, by Visconti family and Sforza dukes 14th-15th centuries, then by Hapsburgs.

The state of Rhineland-Palatinate, lying in southwestern Germany, is the ninth largest in the nation, measuring some 7664 square miles. It is bordered by Belgium, Luxembourg, and France to the south and west, and by the German states of North Rhine-Westphalia to the north, Saarland to the southwest, and Hesse and Baden-Württemberg to the east. Its territory has historically been fought over and partitioned among foreign powers. The modern state was created after World War II. Formerly a primarily agricultural state, it now relies mainly on industry and commerce. Its capital city is Mainz. The official census gave the 2005 population as 4,076,208.

Administrative region of Italy. Productive agricultural area from ancient times; settled by Etruscans; taken by Samnites 5th century BCE, supported Greek colonies along coast; was Roman from 4th century BCE; later ruled by Goths, Byzantines, Lombards, and Normans; part of Two Sicilies from 1282.

Lower Saxony is the second largest state of Germany, its area comprising some 47613.35 square kilometers. It lies between The Netherlands in the west and the German states of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and Saxony-Anhalt. It formed part of the historic Sachsen region. The people share a common Saxon origin and a common language, Plattdeutsch, related to Dutch, Frisian, and English. It received an influx of refugees during and after World War II. The modern state is a merger of four older districts: Hannover, Braunschweig, Oldenburg, and Schaumburg, created on November 1, 1946. The 2004 estimated population was 8,004,300.

The region comprises the large island of the same name and several nearby smaller islands. Sicily became a major center of revolutionary movements in the 19th century: as a result of Giuseppe Garibaldi's revolt, it was liberated from the Bourbons in 1860 and in the following year it was incorporated into the united kingdom of Italy. Sicily gained regional autonomy in 1947.

wikidata_description: capital of and state in Austria

scope_note: Inhabited early by Umbri and Picentes people; colonized by Greeks, later by Romans (3rd century BCE); invaded by Goths 5th century CE; portions ruled by Byzantines and Lombards; ruled by Pope in 8th century and again from the 13th century.

Rich agricultural area bordering Adriatic Sea; Emilia and Romagna fell to Lombards 5th century CE; Emilia went to Franks 8th century, duchy of Modena by 17th century, then to Parma and Piacenza; Romagna was ruled by Byzantines 6th century, and by Pope from 16th century.

The east central German state of Saxony consists of the southeastern portion of what was formerly the nation of East Germany. In the 1950s three East German Bezirke, or national districts, were formed of the historic Saxon region. After the reunification of Germany, all or parts of these three districts were made into the German state of Saxony. It measures some 7080 square miles in area and has a population of about 4, 278,000. Its capital is Dresden. Except for the northern portion around Leipzig, which belongs to the North European Plain, the state is mostly mountainous in terrain. It is drained by the Elbe river, which runs northwest to southeast, and the Mulde, a tributary of the Elbe. Saxony's principal mountain range is the Ore Mountains, which run for about 100 miles along its southern border. The state has rich soil and its agriculture is highly developed, grains being important throughout most of the state, while cattle are the main product in the Ore Mountains. Forestry and the mining of tin, lead, and coal are also important. The main industries are the production of textiles and of machinery used in textile production, papermaking, printing, and mining.
Formed of historic Anhalt region & part of historic Sachsen region.

Was home of ancient Umbri tribes, who spoke an Indo-European dialect and were concentrated here to escape Etruscan and Gallic pressure during 1st mill. BCE; later held by Romans, Lombards and Byzantines; city-states developed; went to Papal States in the 16th century.

The northern German state of Bremen, created in 1947, consists of the city of Bremen on the Weser River and the physically separate city of Bremerhaven, 37 miles away on the North Sea. It is the smallest of the states of Germany but is of great economic importance. Its 2004 estimated population was 664,500.

In southern Germany; much of the land is occupied by Thuringian Forest; Harz mountains form its northern border; Thuringian basin is fertile agricultural region, though economy of state is largely industrial.
wikidata_description: federated state in the center of Germany

scope_note: Occupied by Algonquians (Mohican & Munsee) and Iroquois (Five Nations) when Europeans settled here in 17th cen.; French and Algonquians warred with English & Iroquois in 18th cen.; state was divided during Revolution; supported Union in Civil War.
wikidata_description: state of the United States of America

scope_note: Part of the Roman Empire from 1st cen. BCE; established as a political unit by 10th cen.; went to Savoy in 1045; supported feudal states in 12th cen.; was nominal fief of Holy Roman Empire through Middle Ages; held by house of Savoy into 19th cen.

wikidata_description: city and state in the North of Germany

scope_note: Was home to early Apulians and Greek colonists; came under control of republican Rome by 3rd century BCE; taken by Goths, Lombards and Byzantines; was duchy under Normans in 12th century; part of Kingdom of Two Sicilies and later of Holy Roman Empire.

This region constitutes the southern part of the former duchy of Brabant, and contained within the modern nation of Belgium. It is watered by the Senne, Dijle, and Demer rivers. It was occupied by Germany during World Wars I and II. In 1993, the region was split into the provinces of Flemish Brabant and Walloon Brabant.
wikidata_description: province of Belgium until its splitting in 1995

scope_note: The German state of Brandenburg is the remaining core of the historic European  region of Brandenburg. It was created in 1990 when East and West Germany were united, and occupies the east-central and eastern areas of the former East Germany. Its capital is Potsdam. The state and city of Berlin lie in the center of Brandenburg but is a separate administrative entity. Geographically, most of the state consists of a sandy plain with occasional fertile areas and fir and pine woodlands. It measures some 11,219 square miles, and is watered by the Elbe and Oder Rivers, their tributaries, and about 600 lakes. Agriculture is a major economic activity, with cereals, potatoes, wheat, dairying, beef, and fruits and vegetables being important crops. Potsdam, Cottbus, the city of Brandenburg, and Frankfurt an der Oder are its principal cities. Its primary industries are steelmaking, the manufacture of textiles, and engineering. Its population is of relatively low density, the 2004 estimation being 257,100.
Former region of eastern France (until 2016); the area was part of historic Burgundy.

Fertile coastal strip (Italian Riviera) and inland mountains; home to prehistoric Ligurii people, who inhabited Mediterranean coast from Rhône to Arno rivers; visited by Phoenicians & Greeks; taken by Rome 2nd cen. BCE; ruled by Genoa from 13th cen.
Folded into the "Grand Est" region in 2016.
Former administrative division; in 2016, merged with Picardie region to become "Hauts-de-France" region.

Primarily comprises historic Holstein and Schleswig regions; Denmark's annexation of Schleswig brought them to war with Austria and Prussia in 1863; Schleswig-Holstein was annexed to Prussia in 1866, but N Schleswig went back to Denmark in 1920.
An administrative division (region) of France until 2016, when it was merged with the Aquitaine and Limousin regions to form the new region, "Nouvelle-Aquitaine."

The modern region of Aquitaine is roughly coextensive with the western half of the historical region of the same name. It encompasses the départements of Dordogne, Gironde, Landes, Lot-et-Garonne, and Pyrénées-Atlantiques in southwestern France. Conquered by Franks in 507; it was a duchy until 768; made subkingdom by Charlemagne and given to his son Louis 781; to the French crown in 877. It became a powerful feudal duchy controlling most of France south of Loire by the 11th century. Passed to Capetians in 1137, to the English in 1152. An administrative division until 2016, when it was grouped with the Limousin and Poitou-Charentes regions to form the new region, "Nouvelle-Aquitaine."

Former administrative division (through 2016, when it was folded into the "Grand Est" region) located between Rhine river and Vosges mountains; area historically has alternated between French and German rule; see also historic region, Alsace.

The region of Bohemia occupies a portion of central Europe now encompassed by the western Czech Republic, bounded on the north and west by Germany, the south by Austria, on the east by Moravia, and on the northeast by Silesia. It was a kingdom under the Holy Roman Empire and a province under the Austrian Empire of the Hapsburgs. Home to Slavs by the 6th century, the Carolingians brought Christianity in the 8th century. It was independent under King Wenceslaus in 10th century. In 1355, King Charles of Bohemia became the Holy Roman Emperor Charles IV, and Bohemia became part of the empire. From the early 15th century, it suffered continual discord and outright war between Roman Catholics and Protestants. From 1526 the kingdom was under Hapsburg rule and became part of the Austrian Empire. Following a Protestant revolt in 1620 that was suppressed by the Catholic Hapsburgs, Bohemia lost its status as a kingdom and was ruled directed by the Hapsburg emperor. By the mid-18th century it had been thoroughly absorbed into the Austrian Empire and most of the population reverted to Catholicism. This continued until 1918 when it joined with Slovakia to form the nation of Czechoslovakia. Bohemia was occupied by Nazi Germany from 1938, then again became a province of Czechoslovakia after 1945. In 1949 under a Communist government, it ceased to be an integral administrative unit. In 1993 with the division of Czechoslovakia unto Slovakia and the Czech Republic, the region formed central and western parts of the latter.
wikidata_description: historical region in the Czech Republic

scope_note: Essentially flat area in Paris Basin, with oceanic climate; most people live in medium-sized towns; agriculture is highly mechanized and crops include sugar, beets, wheat, barley, and potatoes; see also historic Picardie. In 2016, merged with Nord-Pas-de-Calais region to become the "Hauts-de-France" region.

The province of Antwerpen is located in northern Belgiium on the frontier with the Netherlands. The area is watered by the Schelde River and its tributaries. It was once part of the old duchy of Brabant and became part of the French province of Deux-Nèthes after the French occupation of 1795. Its modern boundaries were established in 1815, although subsequently modified. It is divided into three sections, Antwerp, Mechelen, and Turnhout, with the capital at Antwerp. The 2003 estimated population is about 1,657,200.
Demicanton that functions as a full canton; includes the city of Basel and some small villages; separated from Basel-Landschaft in 19th century, after a rural revolt in 1831.
Administrative division (region) until 2016, when it was merged with the Midi-Pyrénées region, to form the new "Occitanie" region.

wikidata_description: federal state in the South of Austria

scope_note: Region in central Italy, the most mountainous in the Italian Apennines; populated since Paleolithic times; Roman from 304 BCE; part of Lombard duchy of Spoleto 6th-11th centuries CE; part of kingdom of Naples 1266-1860.

Settled by Amerindians by 2nd mill. BCE; Norsemen may have landed here in 1003; Europeans fished here in 16th cen.; Plymouth Colony established by English in 1620; played key role in Revolution; was intellectual center of nation until mid-19th cen.
wikidata_description: state of the United States of America

scope_note: The state of Steiermark is located in the mountainous central and southeast Austria. It was inhabited in Paleolithic times and was the site of mining in the Bronze Age. It was settled by Celts and became part of the Celtic kingdoms of Noricum, later incorporated into the Roman Empire ca. 15 BCE and named Pannonia. Germanic people invaded it in the 5th century CE, followed by the Avars and Slovenes. Bavarians ruled it from ca. 780, and it became a frontier territory of the Frankish Empire. It became a duchy in 1180 and passed to the Babenberg dukes of Austria in 1192, then to the family of Hapsburg in 1276. After World War I part of its southern area was ceded to Yugoslavia. Since then, except for a brief period as a district under the German annexation, 1938-1945, it has been a federal province of Austria.
wikidata_description: federal state in the south of Austria

scope_note: Tyrol is a mountainous region in southwestern Austria, bordering both Germany and Italy. Historically it has been in a strategic position guarding the Brenner Pass. Originally inhabited by Rhaetic tribes, it went to Rome in 15 BCE. Teutonic tribes took it over at the end of the western Roman Empire, then the Franks. The Hapsburgs ruled it from 1363 until 1918. After World War I, South Tyrol became part of Italy, which it remains to this day.
Administrative division (region) until 2016, when it was merged with the Languedoc-Roussillon region, to form the new "Occitanie" region.

wikidata_description: federal state in the North of Austria

scope_note: Mountainous region in northern Italy; was part of Austria in 19th century, and almost half of the population still speaks German as a first language; suffered in WW II after opposing the Fascist plan to "Italianize" the area.

Until 2016, a first level division of France. The region was related to the historic region of Auvergne. It was a planning department of modern France, and its economy was based on animal husbandry in the mountain areas and on wheat and fodder cultivation on the plains. Relatively sparsely populated.
Former administrative region of France. In 2016, it was merged with the former Haute-Normandie region, to create the new region of "Normandie."

Inhabited by many ethnic nationalities including Mojave, Yuma and Chumash when Spanish arrived in 16th cen.; Franciscans established missions all along coast; went to Mexico in 1820s; went to US in 1848; great influx of settlers from E arrived in gold rush.
wikidata_description: state of the United States of America

scope_note: Comprises districts acquired by city of Bern between 14th and 16th centuries; area is drained by Aare river and its affluents; it is divided into three physical regions, the Bernese highland, the midland area including the Aare and Emme valleys, and the lake region.
Administrative division (region) of France until 2016, when it was combined with the region of Basse-Normandie, to form the new region of "Normandie."
Incorporated in France 1532; related to historic region, Bretagne.

Part of Paris Basin except for the massif of the Vosges in the east; contains large iron ore deposits; population is heavily concentrated along Moselle river between Nancy and Thionville; see also the historical region of Lorraine. Administrative division until 2016 when it was folded into the "Grand Est" region.

wikidata_description: federal state in the North-West of Austria

scope_note: Inhabited by 8000 BCE; Mississippian people flourished ca. 1300 CE; had largest pre-Columbian community N of Mexico; various Algonquian tribes were here when French & English settled 17-18th centuries; went to USA in 1778 in Revolution; pro-Union in Civil War.
wikidata_description: state of the United States of America

scope_note: Canada's 2nd largest province; originally inhabited by Huron, Erie, and Petun Indians; ceded by France to Great Britain 1763; nation's most important mining province; produces around half of world's nickel; also contains copper, iron ore, gold and zinc.

Liège is a province in east Belgium, bordered by Germany on the east. It is drained by Meuse, Amblève, Ourthe and Vesdre Rivers. It was the core of the territory held by independent prince-bishops of Lieège for nearly 1000 years. They allied themselves with the Hapsburg rulers of The Netherlands from the 16th century until 1795 when France annexed it. Assigned to The Netherlands in 1815, the lands became Belgian in 1830. The land supports a wide variety of agriculture, and there are several major industrial areas. There are two natural wild preserves. There are many old castles and monasteries, and tourism is important, especially at Spa and along the Ourthe and Amblève Rivers. The province is mainly French speaking with a few German-speaking areas. The 2003 estimated population was 1,027,100.

Settled in prehistoric times; was powerful Greek colonial area; taken by Romans in 268 BCE, by Byzantine Empire in 9th century CE, and by Normans in the 11th century; was center of Italian republicanism and united to Kingdom of Italy 1860.

Part of kingdom of Burgundy 5th century.; part of kingdom of Arles; went to Holy Roman Empire in 12th century; under duchy of Burgundy from 1384; went to Spanish Hapsburgs via Charles V; occupied by Louis XIV in 17th century. Merged into the Bourgogne region in 2016 to form Bourgogne-Franche-Comté.

Located off the Gulf of Taranto; was under Lombard rule in early Middle Ages; ruled by dukes of Benevento & princes of Salerno; went to Byzantines, then Normans, Angevins & Spanish; was coextensive with Potenza province until Matera was created in 1927.

Comprises part of the Engadine valley and sources of Rhine and Inn rivers; was part of Roman province of Raetia; conquered by Franks in 6th century CE; part of Germany from 10th century; accepted Reformation doctrine in 1526.

Hainaut, a province in southwestern Belgium, stretches northeastward from the French border and is watered by three rivers, the Schelde, the Dender, and the Sambre. Occupied successively by the  Celtic-German tribe of the Nervii, the Romans, and the Merovingians, the province was part of the great medieval county of Hainaut, which at its peak was larger than all of modern Belgium. After centuries of rule by Holland, the area was taken by France and held by it from 1659. It passed to the Netherlands in 1814, whence it passed to Belgium in 1831. The land is rich in agricultural land and coal, and industries include coal mining, steel, textiles, chemicals, glass, wire and machine tools. The province boasts of over 100 castles. It has an area of 1,462 square miles and its 2003 estimated population was 1,284,700.
Located in the Lepontine Alps; was part of Roman Transpadane Gaul; part of Lombardy until 15th century, when Swiss Confederation took area from Milan; ruled by Uri and Schwyz cantons until 1798.

Occupied mainly by Algonquian, with Iroquoian-speakers in E, when English, Dutch and Swedes settled here 17th cen.; haven for religious dissenters founded by W Penn in 1682; suffered battles in French and Indian wars; was strongly pro-Revolution and pro-Union.
wikidata_description: state of the United States of America

scope_note: Region comprises the large island of the same name and several nearby small islands.

Occupies an elevated plain, bisected by Saane river; evidence of prehistoric settlements exists on shores of Neuchâtel and Morat lakes; today area is predominantly agricultural; located on linguistic frontier of nation.
Located in southwest tip of nation, between Jura mountains and the Alps; drained by Rhône river.

Originally inhabited by 16 tribes of Algonquian Indians; Dutchman, A Block, was first European in the area; English arrived in 1633, battled with Amerindians & Dutch; area provided supplies for Revolution; characterized today by rural & shore communities.
wikidata_description: state of the United States of America

scope_note: Borders France and Switzerland; originally inhabited by Salassi people; was part of Roman Empire under Augustus; part of Savoy in 11th cen.; was historically important because 3 crucial routes through the Alps converge in this area.
wikidata_description: Italian mountainous semi-autonomous region in the North-West

scope_note: Located along the Italian border; area has been inhabited since prehistoric times; occupied by Rome under Julius Caesar from 57 BCE; passed to bishop of Sion in 999; remained Catholic throughout the Reformation.
Comprises land acquired by Luzern city; part of Helvetic Republic after 1798; population is mainly Roman Catholic and language is German.

Located in northeast Switzerland, made up of productive, shallow river valleys, lakes, and forests; contains land acquired by city of Zürich up to 1803; population is largely Protestant and the main language is German.
Area has been inhabited since prehistoric times; was first consolidated as a political unit in 8th century CE; ruled by dukes of Zähringen and counts of Kyburg, then Hapsburgs (1274).

Inhabited by Ojibwa, Ottawa, Potawatomi and others when French arrived in 18th cen.; taken by England in 1760s, by USA in Revolution and again in War of 1812; most Amerindians were forced west in 19th cen.; pro-Union in Civil War, noted for African regiment.
wikidata_description: state of the United States of America

scope_note: Area was homeland of the Hapsburg dynasty in 11th century; captured by Swiss Confederation in 1415 and divided between Bern and Lucerne; was reunited in 1803.

Inhabited by 5000 BCE; center for Hopewell culture before 400 CE; home to Miami, Shawnee, Wyandot, Delaware and others when French & British arrived 17-18th cen.; Amerindians supported British in Revolution; 300,000 soldiers fought for Union in Civil War.
wikidata_description: state of the United States of America

scope_note: The province of Namur lies in the southeast of Belgium bounded on the north by Brabant, on the northeast by Liége, on the east by the province of Luxembourg, on the south by France, and on the west by Hainaut. The Meuse, Sambre, and Lesse Rivers cross it. Formerly its eastern part was ruled by the prince-bishops of Liège, while its northern part was the medieval county of Namur. Transferred to Hainaut in 1188, it temporarily became a marquisate in 1199, was ceded to Flanders in 1263, and then sold to the Duke of Burgundy in 1421.As part of the Burgundian Netherlands it became part of Belgium in 1830. Its land supports a wide variety of agriculture, while the Sambre and Meuse Valleys are part of the "industrial crescent" of southern Belgium. Tourists are drawn to resorts along the Meuse River and to medieval chateaus and abbeys throughout the province. Its area covers some 3,666 square miles in all. The 2003 estimated population was 449,100.

The northwest Belgian province of Oost-Vlaanderen was historically part of the medieval duchy of Flanders. A great textile-producing region since the Middle Ages, it continues as such, producing cotton, jute, rayon, and nylon, along with lace, linen, and some wool. Agriculturally, it produces potatoes, flax, hops, market vegetables, sugar beets, and livestock. The capital city is Ghent. One of Europe's most densely populated areas, it covers some 1,151 square miles and has a population, by a 2003 estimate, of 1,370,600.

Comprises districts acquired by city of Bern between 14th and 16th centuries; area is drained by Aare river and its affluents; it is divided into three physical regions, the Bernese highland, the midland area including the Aare and Emme valleys, and the lake region.
Demicanton that functions as full canton.

Limburg is a largely Flemish-speaking province of northeastern Belgium once part of the historic county of Limburg, which was divided between The Netherlands and Belgium in 1839. It is bounded by The Netherlands on the north and east, where the Meuse River marks the frontier. Its agricultural products include wheat, sugar beets, fruit and dairy products, notably the Limburger cheese that originated there. It also produces most of Belgium's coal. Its total territory covers about 935 square miles and, by a 2003 estimate, has a population of about 800,900.

The westernmost province of Belgium it runs inward from the North Sea, bordering the Netherlands on the east and France on the west and south. It once was part of the historic duchy of Flanders. Its southwest region was a major battleground for trench warfare during World War I and underwent great destruction, and many towns such as Ypres have been rebuilt. It is the leading agricultural province of Belgium, producing wheat, sugar beets, potatoes, tobacco and cattle. The main industries are shipbuilding, chemical production, lacemaking, and metallurgical industries. Tourism is extremely important along the coast, which features several seaside resorts, Ostend chief among them. It covers 1,214 square miles in area, and has a population, by a 2003 estimate, of 1,135,500.

Located in northeast Switzerland, made up of productive, shallow river valleys, lakes, and forests; contains land acquired by city of Zürich up to 1803; population is largely Protestant and the main language is German.

Originally inhabited by Algonkin, Montagnais and Cree Indians; Eskimos later settled in Hudson Bay area; region declared for France by Jacques Cartier who landed at Gaspé 1534; settlement of colony of New France commenced at present Québec City 1608.
Demicanton that functions as a full canton; formed in 19th century when Basel canton was divided into 2 demicantons, after rural part of the canton revolted in 1831.

Saarland is a state of southwestern Germany, bordered by the German state of Rhineland-Palatinate on the north and east, by Luxembourg on the west, and France on the south. Its area encompasses some 992 square miles on both sides of the Saar river. The capital is Saarbrücken. The state generally is rich in coal deposits and is known for its iron and steel industries. It was a prime producer of armaments and weaponry in World War II and thus was a major target for Allied bombing, suffering great destruction. The calculated population for 2005 was 1,061,840.
wikidata_description: state of the Federal Republic of Germany

scope_note: Occupied by roving hunters by ca. 8000 BC, later was home to agrarian cultures; Algonquian-speakers, at war with Iroquois to N, lived here when Europeans settled in 17th cen.; fought in Revolution; state had split loyalties in Civil War.

This region constitutes the southern part of the former duchy of Brabant, and contained within the modern nation of Belgium. It is watered by the Senne, Dijle, and Demer rivers. The province lies in Wallonie in southeast Belgium, has an area of 1,715 square miles and is drained by three tributaries of the Meuse River: the Ourthe, Semois, and Lesse Rivers. It is bounded by the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg to the east, France to the south, and the provinces of Namur to the west and Liège to the north.75% of it lies within the Ardennes Plateau, and one-third of that is woodland. The remaining 25% constitutes the Belgian Lorraine. The province was once a part of the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg but became part of Belgium in 1831. Its northern area was heavily damaged during the Second World War, particularly during the Battle of the Bulge in 1944-1945. Its historic structures include the ruined castle at Bouillon and the restored Cistercian Abbey of Orval near Florenville. Tourism is important in the area covered by the Ardennes forest, which has two nature reserves. Agricultural products include oats, rye, wheat, potatoes, tobacco, and livestock, while mining is mostly of iron and building stone. The 2003 estimated population was 251,100.

Moravia is a region in the Czech Republic, bounded by Silesia on the northeast, Bohemia on the west and northwest, Austria to the south, and Slovakia on the east. It was home to Celtic Bori and Cotini peoples from the fourth century BCE.  Germanic tribes arrived in the period from the first to the fifth century CE, then the Avars in the sixth and seventh centuries, then a Slavic people called the Moravians, after the Morava River, in the late eighth century. It became an independent kingdom in the ninth century, Great Moravia, which comprised all of Bohemia, the southern part of modern Poland, and the western part of modern Hungary. Great Moravia dissolved with the death of its king Svatopluk in 894 and an overwhelming attack by the Magyars. Its lands were variously taken over by Hungary, Poland, and Bohemia. To Bohemia went Moravia proper, which was incorporated as a province in 1029. It came under the rule of the Austria Hapsburgs in 1526 together with Bohemia and Silesia. In the centuries of religious strife and rebellion that followed, Moravia was less rebellious than Bohemia and its largely Protestant population suffered less. Late in the 18th century what remained of Austrian Silesia was merged into Moravia and after 1848 it became an Austrian crown land with some autonomy. In 1918 it was joined to the new nation of Czechoslovakia. In 1949 it ceased to be a single administrative unit, being divided into several smaller provinces by the Czechoslovakian government. In 1960, the territory formerly known as Moravia and Silesia became Jihomoravsky, or South Moravia, and Severomoravsky, or North Moravia. These became part of the Czech Republic in 1993.

scope_note: The east central German state of Saxony consists of the southeastern portion of what was formerly the nation of East Germany. In the 1950s three East German Bezirke, or national districts, were formed of the historic Saxon region. After the reunification of Germany, all or parts of these three districts were made into the German state of Saxony. It measures some 7080 square miles in area and has a population of about 4, 278,000. Its capital is Dresden. Except for the northern portion around Leipzig, which belongs to the North European Plain, the state is mostly mountainous in terrain. It is drained by the Elbe river, which runs northwest to southeast, and the Mulde, a tributary of the Elbe. Saxony's principal mountain range is the Ore Mountains, which run for about 100 miles along its southern border. The state has rich soil and its agriculture is highly developed, grains being important throughout most of the state, while cattle are the main product in the Ore Mountains. Forestry and the mining of tin, lead, and coal are also important. The main industries are the production of textiles and of machinery used in textile production, papermaking, printing, and mining.

The German state of Brandenburg is the remaining core of the historic European  region of Brandenburg. It was created in 1990 when East and West Germany were united, and occupies the east-central and eastern areas of the former East Germany. Its capital is Potsdam. The state and city of Berlin lie in the center of Brandenburg but is a separate administrative entity. Geographically, most of the state consists of a sandy plain with occasional fertile areas and fir and pine woodlands. It measures some 11,219 square miles, and is watered by the Elbe and Oder Rivers, their tributaries, and about 600 lakes. Agriculture is a major economic activity, with cereals, potatoes, wheat, dairying, beef, and fruits and vegetables being important crops. Potsdam, Cottbus, the city of Brandenburg, and Frankfurt an der Oder are its principal cities. Its primary industries are steelmaking, the manufacture of textiles, and engineering. Its population is of relatively low density, the 2004 estimation being 257,100.

Baden-Württemberg is a state in southwestern Germany, bordered by Switzerland in the south, France to the west, the state of Bavaria on the east, Rhineland-Palatinate on the northeast, and Hesse to the north. It measures some 13,804 square miles in area. Most of its people are Alemanni, relatives of the French Alsatians, plus Franconians, Palatinate people, and Swabians. Before the Romans occupied it, the main European trading artery was the River Rhein which runs through Baden-Württemberg. It also had immense hardwood forests, now largely cut. To the south are the Alps. The state was formed in the post-World War II occupational period from three former states in the American and French zones; this arrangement was ratified by a referendum in 1951 and made official in 1952. Its capital is Stuttgart. The 2004 estimated population was 10,721,600.
